# Code of Conduct

## Our commitment

This project welcomes contributors of all backgrounds and experience levels. We
are committed to providing a friendly, safe, and respectful environment for
everyone — whether you're opening your first issue or you're a seasoned security
professional.

## Expected behaviour

- Be respectful, considerate, and constructive in all interactions.
- Welcome newcomers and help them learn; assume good intent.
- Give and accept feedback graciously — critique the work, not the person.
- Respect differing viewpoints and experiences.
- Keep discussion focused on what's best for the project and its community.

## Unacceptable behaviour

- Harassment, insults, or derogatory comments of any kind.
- Discriminatory language or imagery, or unwelcome personal attention.
- Personal or political attacks.
- Publishing others' private information without permission.
- Sharing real credentials, exploit code intended to cause harm, or any content
  that violates this project's defensive-security purpose.
- Any other conduct that would reasonably be considered inappropriate in a
  professional setting.

## Scope

This Code of Conduct applies within all project spaces — issues, pull requests,
discussions, and any other project communication — and when an individual is
representing the project in public spaces.

## Reporting

If you experience or witness unacceptable behaviour, please report it privately
to the project maintainer through GitHub — for example by using GitHub's
private reporting features, or by contacting the maintainer via their GitHub
profile. All reports will be reviewed and handled with discretion. The
maintainer is committed to protecting the privacy and safety of anyone who
reports an issue in good faith.

## Enforcement

The maintainer may take any action deemed appropriate, up to and including
removing comments, rejecting contributions, or blocking contributors who violate
this Code of Conduct.

## Attribution

This Code of Conduct is adapted from the [Contributor Covenant](https://www.contributor-covenant.org),
a widely used standard for open-source communities.
